# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brännboll
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:brännboll/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:brännboll/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:brännboll/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:brännboll/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:brännboll/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:brännboll/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:brännboll/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:brännboll/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:brännboll/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:brännboll/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:brännboll/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:brännboll/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:brännboll/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:brännboll/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Although similar to paintball in concept and gameplay, airsoft pellets do not leave visible dye markings on their target and hits are not always apparent, though the pellets can sometimes leave small bruises or welts on exposed skin (and so protective gear is still recommended).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The game therefore relies heavily on an honor system in which players who have been hit are expected to call themselves out of play in keeping with honesty, fairness and sportsmanship.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The airsoft guns used are mostly magazine-fed, with some having manual/battery motor-powered spring-piston pump power plants similar to Nerf Blasters, or pneumatically powered by replaceable compressed gas (e.g. propane ("green gas"), 1,1,1,2-tetrafluoroethane or CO2) canisters.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Many airsoft guns also have mounting platforms compatible with genuine firearm accessories, and most cosmetically resemble real firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] This makes them popular for military simulation and historical reenactments.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] There are also professional gun safety and weapon manipulation training conducted with airsoft in some fields, such as law enforcement training, due to better safety and lower cost.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The United States Coast Guard, for instance, officially adopted airsoft for training in 2018.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft gameplay varies in style and composition, but often ranges from action shooting to short organized live action role-playing (LARP) scenarios, close quarters battle skirmishes, military simulations (MilSim) or historical reenactments.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It is played in indoor courses or outdoor fields.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Combat situations on the field may involve the use of genuine military tactics to achieve objectives set in each game.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Participants may attempt to emulate the tactical equipment and accessories used by modern military and police organizations.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] A game is normally kept safe by trained professionals acting as supervisors and marshals.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Before gameplay, an airsoft gun's muzzle velocity is usually checked through a chronograph and usually measured in feet per second (FPS) or joules, a measurement for kinetic energy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some countries have a set velocity or muzzle energy restriction; guns shooting over the legal muzzle velocity can be confiscated.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some playing fields further restrict minimum engagement distances, requiring players to yell "Bang Bang!" or other verbal phrases in order to prevent shooting other players at close distances, which may cause injury.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In certain countries use of laser sights of any kind is illegal, including gun scopes with integrated lasers.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft originated in postwar Japan during the early 1970s, when photographer Ichiro Nagata, an avid shooting enthusiast himself, thought about making modelguns that shoot real projectiles that could not kill or wound.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Early airsoft guns use a manual spring-piston design and are essentially single-shot, tailoring to the needs of shooting enthusiasts while conforming to Japan's strict weapons control laws.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Originally designed for target shooting, the plastic balls used in these "guns" can be shot at humans without causing injury due to the low muzzle energy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These new-generation replica guns were trademarked as **soft air guns** because the refrigerant propellant used was significantly weaker ("soft") than the canistered CO2 used in proper airguns (pellet guns and BB guns).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] This practical convenience of AEGs led soft air guns to quickly become popular for casual MilSim games, which the Japanese call **survival games** (サバイバルゲーム, *sabaibaru gēmu*).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Asahi Firearms was also a model company from Japan who operated in the 1980s and 90s and was one of the early pioneers of the airsoft hobby.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft guns spread to the United Kingdom in the late 1980s and early 1990s via a company called LS.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They were sold in separate pieces and had to be assembled out-of-box before they were capable of shooting.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These then became available to the rest of Europe and North America and rapidly gained popularity worldwide.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Since the mid-1980s, airsoft has been adapted with a purely recreational application in mind, and the sport is enjoyed by all ages.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft replicas are produced globally, with the majority being manufactured in East Asia.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Many law enforcement agencies and military units within the United States now start using airsoft for force-on-force tactical training drills.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The guns used in airsoft are typically classified as imitation firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They have a mechanism for shooting projectiles 6 mm, 6.4 mm, or 8 mm in diameter.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some companies produce full replicas of counterpart grenade launchers which fire a projectile spray of 6 millimetres (0.24 in) pellets by use of a high-powered spring mechanism or a compressed gas propellant (i.e. green gas, propane, compressed air, or CO2).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] There is also a type of airsoft gun that is powered by a single (HPA) high-pressure air tank and a battery pack to power the internal FCU "Fire Control Unit" computer board.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These guns are often known for their high and adjustable RPS or "Rounds Per Second" and durability.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These HPA replicas are most often referred to as "PolarStars", although this refers to a popular brand of HPA engines and accessories.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] A typical airsoft gun is noticeably lighter than its "real steel" counterpart due to the use of aluminum alloy and plastic materials, though some have added weights in them for a more realistic feel.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Japan has specific rules about producing airsoft guns with metal parts, while newer guns, especially those made in Taiwan and Mainland China, have both internal and external parts that are metallic.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Smoke caps, as well as noise amplifiers, are available for certain airsoft guns to add realism.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Gas handgun magazines usually contain 10 to 30 pellets in a standard-capacity magazine; however, some are high-capacity magazines and can hold 50 rounds or more.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In the case of AEG rifles, magazines come in either real-capacity (equivalent to the 30-round capacity of its real steel counterpart), low-capacity (10–50 rounds), mid-capacity (75–250 rounds), or high-capacity (250+ rounds).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These magazines have spring followers like in BB guns.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The high-cap magazines often have a ratchet wheel that can be wound up periodically to force pellets up from the holding chamber of the magazine to the feeding chute.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Due to loose pellets in the reservoir, they often make a rattling noise when running or walking.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some airsoft guns have a battery-powered box or drum magazine that holds thousands of pellets, but these are usually only used and allowed on LMGs (light machine gun) type replicas.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It is common for owners to "tech" (modify) their guns.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The majority of gearboxes are made to Tokyo Marui specifications and have aftermarket upgrade parts available commercially.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some gearboxes are proprietary in design.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It is also possible to perform DIY modifications.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The "hop-up" system, which is installed in most stock airsoft rifles and pistols, is used to increase effective ranges by putting backspin on the pellets.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The Magnus effect causes the pellets to experience more lift as they are shot, counteracting against gravity.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] A small rubber nub protrudes into the top of the barrel through a small hole, applies pressure on a rubber bucking, and catches the top of the pellet as it moves past.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Adjusting the hop-up makes the nub more or less protrude into the bucking, so that backspin is increased or reduced.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Ideally, the hop-up should be adjusted so that the pellets fly as far as possible in a straight line without curving upward too far or dropping too quickly.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Hop-Up does decrease the muzzle velocity (a gun firing 340 ft/s (100 m/s) with the hop fully unwound can drop to as low as 300 ft/s (91 m/s)).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Ease and location of adjustment vary by gun design; some equipment provides a control that can be adjusted quickly during gameplay, while others may require partial disassembly.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] For example, a common location for Hop-Up adjustment is where the ejection port would be on a real firearm, which allows the machine to be covered while still allowing quick access to adjust the Hop-Up.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some players customize their airsoft guns, either to improve performance or for purely aesthetic reasons.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Additions include scopes, fore-grips, and flashlights, red dot sights being the most commonly used.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Red dot sights are used to help aim, fore-grips are used to get a better grip on the airsoft gun, and flashlights (whether mounted or held in another hand) are used to illuminate dark areas and/or to blind opponents.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Even though in certain countries lasers are illegal, they are popular attachments in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Also available are "mock suppressors/silencers".
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These resemble the actual firearm accessory that dampens sound.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Since Airsoft does not use combustibles for propulsion these usually serve no function.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Although there are models that function to "light up" a glow-in-the-dark BB using UV light similar to a tracer round.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most airsoft guns fire round plastic pellets, usually white, but Tracers are common as well.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The pellets mostly range from 0.12 to 0.48 g.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] However, the most popular weights for AEGs (automatic electric guns) and GBB* (Gas Blow-Back guns) are 0.20 g to 0.32 g (whose muzzle velocity ranges from approximately 250 ft/s (76 m/s) to 400 ft/s (120 m/s)).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Heavier rounds (0.36–0.40 g) are typically used in long-range and sniper applications since they are more stable in flight and less easily deflected by wind.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The pellets, which are called BBs (ball bearings), are usually bought in bags or bottles of 2,000 to 5,000, but other sizes are available, such as a 250,000 round (65 kg) package of tournament grade BBs.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Biodegradable BBs are a fraction more expensive than non-bio counterparts, but many fields require them.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] BBs are typically 5.95mm ±0.01 mm in diameter.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Due to the low muzzle energy (less than 1.5 J or 1.1 ft⋅lb even for high-power models) and poor sectional density, the pain an airsoft pellet causes on skin impact is about the same as getting pinched.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] As a reference value, a standard 0.20 gram 6 mm pellet, which is the most common size and weight, traveling at 100 m/s (330 ft/s) has 1 J (0.74 ft⋅lb) of kinetic energy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Calculating the kinetic energy of an airsoft projectile is important for ensuring player safety.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] While a projectile’s ability to cause injury or penetrate a surface technically depends on energy density—that is, the kinetic energy divided by the impact area—this variable is nearly constant in airsoft, as most BBs have standardized diameters of 6 mm or 8 mm.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] As a result, the primary factor affecting the potential for injury or penetration is simply the kinetic energy of the BB.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Despite this, safety limits in airsoft are often expressed solely in FPS, which fails to account for variations in BB mass.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] where m is the mass in kilograms and v is the speed in meters per second.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Different regions vary in the velocity airsoft guns are allowed to shoot at.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In the United States, velocity differs from the type of gameplay field.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Close Quarter Battle arenas typically regulate velocity on airsoft guns at around 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] For outdoor fields, velocity is usually regulated by the type of gun.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] With a standard 0.20 grams (3.1 gr) pellet, fully automatic Airsoft Electric Guns (AEGs) are often set at less than 120 m/s (400 ft/s), semi-automatic DMR-style AEGs at 120–140 m/s (400–450 ft/s), and bolt-action (manually cocked spring-piston) sniper rifles at 140–150 m/s (450–500 ft/s).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The maximum effective range of field-legal airsoft guns is around 100 m (110 yd) with a highly upgraded sniper rifle replica.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most airsoft guns used for field play will have an effective range of around 43–67 m (47–73 yd), depending on the intended gameplay role.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most Airsoft guns are capable of shooting from 60 to 125 m/s (200 to 410 ft/s), although it is also possible to purchase upgraded internals that will enable the gun to shoot up to 170 m/s (550 ft/s) or higher.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In California, a common limit for CQB is 110 m/s (350 ft/s).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In Ireland, Italy and Japan the muzzle energy limit for airsoft guns is 1 joule no matter what the type of gameplay.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In the UK, the law allows weapons locked to semi-automatic and bolt-action rifles to fire up to 2.5 joules (at muzzle velocity up to 158 m/s or 518 ft/s).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Any weapon "which is capable of discharging two or more missiles successively without repeated pressure on the trigger" is limited, by law, at 1.3 joules (velocity up to 114 m/s or 374 ft/s).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Northern Ireland has a maximum velocity of 100 m/s (330 ft/s) with 0.20 g pellets, without regard to the type of equipment.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In Sweden, the legal limitations of airsoft guns caps the energy limit at 10 joules for manual guns, and 3 joules for semi- and fully automatic guns.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The ballistics of spring- or electrically powered airsoft guns differ from real firearms in that a longer barrel will not always result in better accuracy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The "sweet spot" for barrel length in a spring/electric powered airsoft gun is around 450 mm (18 in), beyond which added barrel length will not improve accuracy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In any case, barrel quality, velocity consistency, and hopup quality/design are more important factors with regard to accuracy.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Added barrel length will result in slightly increased velocity if the cylinder size and compression are appropriate for the barrel length.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] For example, a gun with a large cylinder and a long barrel will shoot slightly harder than a gun with a small cylinder and a short barrel (*ceteris paribus*).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] This rule will apply even for barrels longer than 500 mm (20 in), if there is enough cylinder volume and air compression to propel the pellet through the barrel.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] However, the resulting velocity increase will be hardly noticeable.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The only considerable advantage of using a longer inner barrel in an AEG or spring-powered gun is that it generally will make the gun quieter due to the weakened muzzle pop.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In gas-powered guns, added barrel length (to an appropriate extent) can result in increased velocity and accuracy to a degree.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Tighter-bore barrels will increase velocity because there will be less space between the pellet and the barrel for the air to escape through.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most stock airsoft guns have 6.03–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) bore barrels, but best performance is usually seen with "tightbore" barrels, which are 6.01–6.05 mm (0.237–0.238 in) in diameter.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] However, the tighter the bore, the more likely the chance of a pellet jam, and subsequently, tightbores need to be cleaned and lubricated regularly.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It is generally agreed upon that a high-quality 6.01-6.02 mm barrel will provide the highest muzzle velocity, while a good-quality 6.03 mm or 6.05 mm barrel will provide the best compromise between power, accuracy and ease of maintenance.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The actual accuracy difference between tightbore sizes is debatable and usually outweighed by bore consistency.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Although, with the newfound popularity with HPA guns, the debate has been opened that barrels with a larger diameter (up to 6.13 mm or 0.241 in) could provide a more accurate shot.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Due to the higher volume of air surrounding the pellet it negates the chance of the pellet coming into contact with the barrel, throwing the pellet's trajectory off, similar to a musket, in how the bullet slams about before leaving the barrel.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft guns are not to be confused with BB guns, which are airguns that shoot 4.5 mm (.177 in) metallic spherical pellets, unlike the plastic pellets shot by airsoft guns.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Many manufacturers and retailers suggest treating an airsoft gun like a real gun at all times.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] This will help alleviate safety issues resulting in an accidental/negligent discharge, or prevent a public panic due to a carelessly displayed airsoft gun being mistaken for a real firearm.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most manufacturers include an orange tip on the muzzle of the airsoft gun for signaling and safety purposes, and most retailers urge consumers not to remove the orange tip as it is used to help distinguish them from a real firearm.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The orange tip serves many purposes, one of them being for law enforcement to help discern airsoft guns from real firearms and thus prevent unnecessary excessive forces.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The minimum safe level of gear required to participate in most games includes a pair of ANSI Z87.1 eye protection, preferably a fully sealed APEL-rated ballistic eyewear.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Traditional prescription glasses and sunglasses, or goggles not rated sufficiently for impact-resistance, may shatter and/or be perforated upon being struck when used for airsoft or paintball, causing injury to the eye.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Masks, face shields and other types of full-face coverings such as balaclavas are recommended at most airsoft fields.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Rules such as a maximum muzzle velocity and engagement distance guidelines are used by different groups.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some organizations have created common safety rules and guidelines.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most minimum engagement distances are 10 feet (3.0 m).
[src:brännboll/airsoft] When not actively playing, some fields require "barrel bags", also known as barrel socks, barrel condoms, barrel blockers, or barrel sleeves, to be placed over the muzzle of the gun.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The magazine is usually removed as well, and the gun fired to clear the chamber.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most fields also require players to leave their guns set to the safety position when they are not shooting, a practice common when using real firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In certain countries, such as the Philippines, additional special rules have been adopted.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft is legal in most parts of the world.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some countries have specific restrictions, such as maximum muzzle velocity and "unrealistic" coloring to distinguish them from actual firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They are legal throughout the United States, but restrictions do exist in cities like Chicago and Detroit.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The states of New Mexico, New York and New Jersey, however, do not allow airsoft guns to be used or handled publicly because of the resemblance to real firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They may be used on private property with the consent of the owner.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Customs and Border Protection FAQ page states that Airsoft guns are considered look-alike firearms which require the special blaze orange marking.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In Ireland, Airsoft guns are classified as Realistic Imitation Firearms but not restricted as much as in the United Kingdom.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Under the Criminal Justice Act of 2006, Airsoft guns are legal in the Republic.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] One can buy, sell and import Airsoft guns without notifying relevant law enforcement authorities.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They do not need to be painted in fluorescent colours, they do not need to have an orange tip, but they cannot launch the projectile with a kinetic energy exceeding 1 joule.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] However, carrying an imitation firearm in public is prohibited, and a gun carry case is required, as for real firearms.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft shops are spread over the country, and buyers must be aged 18 or over to purchase an airsoft gun.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] There is no age limit on Airsoft, as long as a minor has an adult's permission.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In the United Kingdom, most Airsoft guns are classified as realistic imitation firearms or RIFs.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The sale, manufacture, or importation (but not gifting) of these is illegal under the Violent Crime Reduction Act 2006.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] A defence is allowed for selling for specific purposes including airsoft skirmishing.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The minimum age for buying any imitation firearm in the UK is 18.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It is an offence to possess an imitation firearm in a public place without a reasonable excuse, for example traveling to, or from, or being at an airsoft skirmish site.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Most UK airsoft sites and retailers participate in the United Kingdom Airsoft Retailer Association Ltd (UKARA) registration scheme.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] A player who has participated in at least 3 skirmishes over a period of at least 56 days at the same skirmish site can be registered by that site.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Retailers have access to the database to verify that the purchaser can provide them with a defence.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The Border Agency also has access to check legality of imports.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] As an alternative to RIFs, IFs (Imitation Firearms, including 'two tones') are available in the UK.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] These are RIFs which have been painted a bright colour (excluding white/silver/gold) over at least 51% of the item.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] No specific defence is required for selling an IF, although the minimum age for purchasing remains 18.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In Canada, there are laws pertaining to airsoft importing.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] All airsoft guns that are bought in Canada are legal, but when importing it, the gun has to have between 366FPS and 500FPS to pass inspection at customs, otherwise the gun will be shipped back or destroyed.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft guns in the United States are sold with a federally mandated orange tip which must be 1/4 inch or longer covering the muzzle of the replica.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft technology is used in military training and law enforcement training.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Due to airsoft's realism, relatively safe projectiles, and economical ammunition, it is well-suited to war games and force-on-force scenarios to train and improve troop's tactical proficiency via associative learning and stress inoculation.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Multiple airsoft inventions were developed originally for military and law enforcement use.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Marking rounds were invented by Kerry T.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Bowden to allow trainees to see where each projectile landed.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Much like paintball and simunitions, these marking pellets would break upon impact, marking the target with luminescent liquid.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Unlike traditional plastic pellets, marking rounds are heavier to ensure breakage of the shell on impact.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The weight can be adjusted by adding heavier liquid.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Marking rounds are critical for trainees because they allow the shooter to see exactly where they hit the target.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] This allows them to extrapolate their mistakes and improve their aim.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Reusable grenades were improved by Scott Frank to emulate the fragmentation of a real grenade in war games and scenarios.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The grenade can be loaded with paint or pellets.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] It uses a quick release of highly pressurized gas to break the shell and quickly disperse pellets or paint in all directions.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Frank's grenade, although not the first, aimed to be as realistic and predictable as an actual grenade.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] He developed a more accurate timing mechanism and secondary safety mechanisms to prevent accidental discharge.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Both marking rounds and reusable grenades gave airsoft the edge it needed to enter into military and law enforcement training grounds.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The airsoft guns used for training differ from civilian models.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Guns manufactured for professional training are made to replicate the weight, feel and the sound of its real steel counterpart.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] In general, professional training airsoft guns are GBB models and enhanced with a weighted blowback mechanism to increase the force of the kick.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Some are AEGs and are built with a blowback mechanism.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] They are also outfitted with muzzle protectors that amplify the sound to a decibel level comparable to that of a real firearm.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] The average FPS for professional training airsoft guns is higher than civilian models.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Economically, airsoft is cheaper than simulation training.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Benjamin Kratz, Fort Jackson's battalion executive officer, said that one blank M16 round can cost as much as 32 airsoft rounds.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] Airsoft can also be used in military simulations such as in malls or prisons to add to the immersion.
[src:brännboll/airsoft] There are different event producers like MiR Tactical holding these events.
[src:brännboll/amateur] An **amateur** (from French 'one who loves') is generally considered a person who pursues an avocation independent from their source of income.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Amateurs and their pursuits are also described as popular, informal, self-taught, user-generated, DIY, and hobbyist.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Historically, the amateur was considered to be the ideal balance between pure intent, open mind, and the interest or passion for a subject.
[src:brännboll/amateur] That ideology spanned many different fields of interest.
[src:brännboll/amateur] It may have its roots in the ancient Greek philosophy of amateur athletes competing in the Olympics.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The ancient Greek citizens spent most of their time in other pursuits, but competed according to their natural talents and abilities.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The "gentleman amateur" was a phenomenon among the gentry of Great Britain from the 17th century until the 20th century.
[src:brännboll/amateur] With the start of the Age of Reason, with people thinking more about how the world works around them, (see science in the Age of Enlightenment), things like the cabinets of curiosities, and the writing of the book *The Christian Virtuoso*, started to shape the idea of the gentleman amateur.
[src:brännboll/amateur] He was vastly interested in a particular topic, and studied, observed, and collected things and information on his topic of choice.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The Royal Society in Great Britain was generally composed of these "gentleman amateurs", and is one of the reasons science today exists the way it does.
[src:brännboll/amateur] A few examples of these gentleman amateurs are Francis Bacon, Isaac Newton, and Sir Robert Cotton, 1st Baronet, of Connington.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Amateurism can be seen in both a negative and positive light.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Since amateurs often lack formal training and are self-taught, some amateur work may be considered sub-par.
[src:brännboll/amateur] For example, amateur athletes in sports such as basketball, baseball, or football are regarded as possessing a lower level of ability than professional athletes.
[src:brännboll/amateur] On the other hand, an amateur may be in a position to approach a subject with an open mind (as a result of the lack of formal training) and in a financially disinterested manner.
[src:brännboll/amateur] An amateur who dabbles in a field out of interest rather than as a profession, or possesses a general but superficial interest in any art or a branch of knowledge, is often referred to as a dilettante.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Through most of the 20th century the Olympics allowed only amateur athletes to participate and this amateur code was strictly enforced, Jim Thorpe was stripped of track and field medals for having taken expense money for playing baseball in 1912.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Later on, the nations of the Communist Bloc entered teams of Olympians who were all nominally students, soldiers, or working in a profession, but many of whom were in reality paid by the state to train on a full-time basis.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Near the end of the 1960s, the Canadian Amateur Hockey Association (CAHA) felt their amateur players could no longer be competitive against the Soviet team's full-time athletes and the other constantly improving European teams.
[src:brännboll/amateur] They pushed for the ability to use players from professional leagues but met opposition from the International Ice Hockey Federation (IIHF) and the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:brännboll/amateur] At the IIHF Congress in 1969, the IIHF decided to allow Canada to use nine non-NHL professional hockey players at the 1970 World Championships in Montreal and Winnipeg, Manitoba, Canada.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The decision was reversed in January 1970 after IOC President Avery Brundage said that ice hockey's status as an Olympic sport would be in jeopardy if the change was made.
[src:brännboll/amateur] In response, Canada withdrew from all international ice hockey competitions and officials stated that they would not return until "open competition" was instituted.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Günther Sabetzki became president of the IIHF in 1975 and helped to resolve the dispute with the CAHA.
[src:brännboll/amateur] In 1976, the IIHF agreed to allow "open competition" between all players in the World Championships.
[src:brännboll/amateur] However, NHL players were still not allowed to play in the Olympics, because of the unwillingness of the NHL to take a break mid-season and the IOC's amateur-only policy.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Before the 1984 Winter Olympics, a dispute formed over what made a player a professional.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The IOC had adopted a rule that made any player who had signed an NHL contract but played less than ten games in the league eligible.
[src:brännboll/amateur] However, the United States Olympic Committee maintained that any player contracted with an NHL team was a professional and therefore not eligible to play.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The IOC held an emergency meeting that ruled NHL-contracted players were eligible, as long as they had not played in any NHL games.
[src:brännboll/amateur] This made five players on Olympic rosters—one Austrian, two Italians and two Canadians—ineligible.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Players who had played in other professional leagues—such as the World Hockey Association—were allowed to play.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Canadian hockey official Alan Eagleson stated that the rule was only applied to the NHL and that professionally contracted players in European leagues were still considered amateurs.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Murray Costello of the CAHA suggested that a Canadian withdrawal was possible.
[src:brännboll/amateur] In 1986, the IOC voted to allow all athletes to compete in Olympic Games starting in 1988, but let the individual sport federations decide if they wanted to allow professionals.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The act caused the breakup of the Amateur Athletic Union as a wholesale sports governing body at the Olympic level).
[src:brännboll/amateur] Olympic regulations regarding amateur status of athletes were eventually abandoned in the 1990s with the exception of wrestling, where the amateur fight rules are used because professional wrestling is largely staged with predetermined outcomes.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Starting from the 2016 Summer Olympics, professionals were allowed to compete in boxing, though amateur fight rules are still used for the tournament.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Many amateurs make valuable contributions in the field of computer programming through the open source movement.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Amateur dramatics is the performance of plays or musical theater, often to high standards, but lacking the budgets of professional West End or Broadway performances.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Astronomy, chemistry, history, linguistics, and the natural sciences are among the fields that have benefited from the activities of amateurs.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Gregor Mendel was an amateur scientist who never held a position in his field of study.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Radio astronomy was founded by Grote Reber, an amateur radio operator.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Radio itself was greatly advanced by Guglielmo Marconi, a young Italian man who started out by tinkering with a coherer and a spark coil as an amateur electrician.
[src:brännboll/amateur] Pierre de Fermat was a highly influential mathematician whose primary vocation was law.
[src:brännboll/amateur] In the 2000s and 2010s, the distinction between amateur and professional has become increasingly blurred, especially in areas such as computer programming, music and astronomy.
[src:brännboll/amateur] The term amateur professionalism, or pro-am, is used to describe these activities.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] American flag rugby is divided up among four different levels based upon the grade level a child is entering.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] Each division itself has a unique set of rules in recognition that there will be different ability levels between the various age groups.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] The game, while based on rugby union, is actually far more related to rugby sevens.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] Similarities are seen with the number of players on the field and the arrangement of the line-outs, scrums and kick-offs.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] Like rugby union, games are played in halves but the halves are significantly reduced.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] The halves are the same for all four levels at 10 minutes each instead of 40 minutes each.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] The rule differences between each division are minor and gradually shift closer towards rugby union rules as the child advances up in divisions and increases his or her skill set.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] For Owls the game typically revolves around teaching the children to run with the ball, learning to touch the ball down when scoring a try and learning basic passing skills.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] Nothing is contested, there is no kicking, and there are no conversions.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] However, when children reach the Eagle level, many of the prior mentioned restrictions are removed and the children play with contest are allowed open field kicking, and the game has a more dynamic flow to it.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] The first iteration of American flag rugby was founded by Tom Feury in 1998.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] Feury was initially looking for nothing more than a way to get his children and their friends introduced to the game.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] In 1999, the town of Denville granted him access to a field in order to do so.
[src:brännboll/american-flag-rugby] The first year began with only one team and 28 children.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The **Upper Midwest** is a northern subregion of the U.S.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Census Bureau's Midwestern United States.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Although the exact boundaries are not uniformly agreed upon, the region is usually defined to include the states of Iowa, Michigan, Minnesota and Wisconsin, North Dakota, and South Dakota; some definitions include parts of Nebraska and Illinois.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The National Centers for Environmental Information considers the Upper Midwest climate region to include Iowa, Michigan, Minnesota, and Wisconsin.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The Association for Institutional Research in the Upper Midwest includes the states of Iowa, Minnesota, North Dakota, South Dakota, Wisconsin and the upper peninsula of Michigan in the region.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] According to the Library of Congress, the Upper Midwest includes the states of Minnesota, Wisconsin and Michigan.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The region has dramatic variations between summer and winter temperatures: summers are hot, and winters are very cold.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] For example, Sioux Falls averages 25 days each year with temperatures above 90 °F (32 °C) and 45 days each year with temperatures below 5 °F (−15 °C).
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Mitchell, South Dakota has a record high of 116 °F (47 °C) and a record low of −39 °F (−39 °C).
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The growing season is shorter, cooler and drier in areas farther north and west.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The region's western boundary is sometimes considered to be determined by where the climate becomes too dry to support growing non-irrigated crops other than small grains or hay grass.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The Inland North dialect, most prominently characterized by the Northern Cities Vowel Shift, is centered in the eastern part of the Upper Midwest, including Wisconsin, Michigan and the northern parts of Illinois and Ohio; it extends beyond the Midwest into Central and Western New York.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] North Central American English (also known as "Upper Midwestern"), is spoken in Minnesota, parts of Wisconsin and Iowa, the Upper Peninsula of Michigan, portions of Montana and the Dakotas.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The Upper Midwestern monophthong is attributed to the high degree of Scandinavian and German immigration to the region in the late nineteenth century.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The Upper Midwest in the 20th-century was dominated by the Republican Party and was the heartland of the early Progressive movement, the region supporting Theodore Roosevelt's Progressive Party of 1912 and Robert La Follette's Progressive party of 1924.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] During the 1930s and 1940s the Upper Midwestern States were dominated by thirds parties such as the Minnesota Farmer-Labor party, Wisconsin Progressive Party, and the North Dakotan Nonpartisan League.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] In 1938, the National Progressives of America emerged out of the Wisconsin Progressive Party.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The region continues to be favorable to the Democratic Party and moderate Republicans, with Minnesota favoring each Democratic presidential candidate since 1976 and Wisconsin from 1988 to 2012 (and again in 2020).
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Minnesota narrowly supported native Walter Mondale in 1984 in an election where Ronald Reagan won every other state.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Michigan and Illinois also often favor Democratic candidates.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] However, beginning with the 2010 midterm elections, Republicans experienced substantial gains in state legislative and executive offices in Iowa, Minnesota, Wisconsin, and Michigan.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] From 2018, Democrats regained some control of the region.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Upper Midwest states closest to the Great Lakes favor Democrats, and Democratic state trifecta governments formed in Minnesota and Michigan in 2022, though both were broken in 2024.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Great Plains states in the region continue to favor Republicans, with GOP state trifecta governments in the Dakota's and Iowa.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] In 2023, the region had three Democratic governors (in Minnesota, Michigan, and Wisconsin) and three Republican governors (in North Dakota, South Dakota, and Iowa).
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] In the 2020 presidential election, Democrat Joe Biden won the electoral votes of the Blue Wall states of Wisconsin, Michigan, and Minnesota.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Republican Donald Trump won the electoral votes of Iowa, North Dakota, and South Dakota.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Every American state elects two U.S. senators to a six-year term.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] After the November 2020 election, Minnesota and Michigan had two Democratic senators, while North Dakota, South Dakota and Iowa had two Republican senators.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Wisconsin is the only state in the Upper Midwest that has elected one Republican and one Democratic senator.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The economy of the region was largely based upon the mining of iron and copper, as well as a very large timber industry.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Mechanization has sharply reduced employment in those areas, and the economy is increasingly based on tourism.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] Popular interest in the environment and environmentalism, added to traditional interests in hunting and fishing, has attracted a large urban audience who live within driving range.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] The USDA reported that corn, soybean, sunflower and sugar beet crops saw harvest gains in 2018, but were still below the five-year averages.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] In North Dakota, for example, 49% of corn was harvested by November 4 compared with the five-year average of 97%.
[src:brännboll/american-upper-midwest] This was in part due to weather conditions in October that affected the harvest.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The game is mostly played on fields, sports grounds, and in public parks, but it is also part of the PE curriculum in some areas.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The world championship, called Brännbollscupen, is an annual event in the Swedish city of Umeå.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] 'burn-ball') is derived from the act of catching a player between two bases at the end of a batting round, referred to as "burning" them (*bränna*), roughly equivalent to being run out in cricket or out in baseball.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The 'burn-ball' is also the German name for the game, *Brennball*, and in Norway, the name 'burn-ball' (Norwegian: *brentball*) is shared along *slåball* (lit.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Another name is *rundboll*, which is also the Danish name for the game (Danish: *rundbold*), which refers to the act of rounding the field, i.e. a home run (*frivarv/helrunda*, lit.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The game has been known since the 18th century but has only recently reached the same popularity as the closely related ball game long ball.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The rules of brännboll differ between different areas and there is no governing body.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Nevertheless, this section outlines some rules and traditions which are commonly upheld.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] In contrast to baseball and cricket, there is no dedicated pitcher or bowler: but the batters themselves throw or bounce the ball (usually a tennis ball) before hitting it with their bat.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] A selection of bats is sometimes available, with a regular wooden or metallic baseball bat usually present, and a paddle-like bat (known as *klappträ*, washing paddle, or *kärringracket*, "girl racket") resembling a cricket bat available for less experienced batters.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] On some occasions, there is also a stiff racket.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The valid area for a successful batting is usually delimited by natural features such as trees, or simply an agreed upon imaginary border, this rule only restricts how widely the batter can hit, but not how far.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The proportions of the field and positioning of the players are arbitrary, albeit usually adjusted according to the throwing and catching ability of the players, as well as team size.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Some local rules require the catcher to throw the ball at the ground while saying "out".
[src:brännboll/brännboll] If a player from the batting team is caught between two bases at the end of the batting round, they move back to either the last visited base or first base (depending on the local rules) and the catching team scores a point.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] If a batter is unsuccessful at batting after the three attempts allowed, they move to the first base and will run when the next batter bats a valid hit.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] There are no restrictions on the number of players at each base.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Alternatively, the inner team gets to switch sides, as batting is often more lucrative for scoring points.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Each team get to play as both sides, usually one or two times, and sides are shifted at predetermined time intervals.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Score and time is kept by a score keeper, who also has the final say in whether inner team players are caught out at the end of a batting round.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] While not being an organized sport with teams, a league and clearly defined rules, it is appreciated by children of all ages during school or after, and friends after work play for fun.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Since 1974 an annual Students World Championship tournament has been held in the northern city of Umeå, whereby some standardized rules are followed.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The world championship is called Brännbollscupen, which is followed by the festival Brännbollsyran.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Brännboll is enjoyed by elementary schoolchildren in the American Upper Midwest (particularly Minnesota), due to the area's large Scandinavian influence.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] A similar game, brennball, is popular in PE classes at German schools.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] It is usually played indoors, with a larger ball (such as a volleyball or a basketball) and without a bat; batting is replaced by throwing.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The bases are usually far larger than in baseball and more than one player can be on the same base at the same time.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] German brennball is rarely played outside a PE setting.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] In Norway another similar game, called dødball (deadball or deathball), is common.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The game has six or five rings (approximately one meter in diameter) marked on the ground instead of four bases, limiting the number of players secured by a given ring to the amount that can fit within it.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] The term "dead" (død) is used instead of "burnt" or "out".
[src:brännboll/brännboll] When the catcher gets the ball he or she also has to bounce it on the ground (usually on a predetermined square called døboksen, "the death box") and shout "dø" ("die").
[src:brännboll/brännboll] A dead player is exempt from play for the rest of the round unless a home run is achieved; in which case a set number of dead players (usually either one or all of them, depending on the rule-set) are "saved" and allowed to rejoin the queue.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] To complete a run a player has to reenter the "in" side of the field rather than just reaching the last base.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Scoring- and win-conditions varies widely from rule-set to rule-set.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Points can be determined by runs, just by home runs, by rounds won (usually determined by reaching set numbers of home runs for the in-team or dead players for the out-team) or by combinations of the above.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Sometimes points are not used at all and a game ends with no formal winner after a set amount of time.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] Another version of the game, popular among students, is called ölbrännboll (beer-brännball), where beercases are used as bases so the players of the batting team, waiting to run can drink freely.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] It is however not mandatory to drink while waiting.
[src:brännboll/brännboll] One version of the game where drinking *is* mandatory is vinbrännboll (wine-brännball), where you take a glass of wine after passing the fourth base and thus being "safe".
